{"id":"1212.3015","submitter":"Joseph H. Silverman","authors":"Shu Kawaguchi and Joseph H. Silverman","title":"Examples of dynamical degree equals arithmetic degree","comments":"25 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let f : X --> X be a dominant rational map of a projective variety defined\nover a number field. An important geometric-dynamical invariant of f is its\n(first) dynamical degree d_f= lim SpecRadius((f^n)^*)^{1/n}. For algebraic\npoints P of X whose forward orbits are well-defined, there is an analogous\n(upper) arithmetic degree a_f(P) = limsup h_X(f^n(P))^{1/n}, where h_X is an\nample Weil height on X. In an earlier paper, we proved the fundamental\ninequality a_f(P) \\le d_f and conjectured that a_f(P) = d_f whenever the orbit\nof P is Zariski dense. In this paper we show that the conjecture is true for\nseveral types of maps. In other cases, we provide support for the conjecture by\nproving that there is a Zariski dense set of points with disjoint orbits and\nsatisfying a_f(P) = d_f.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Dec 2012 23:45:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-12-14"}
